  <!-- MODULE 1: YOUR GAP REPORT -->
  <div class="apn-s-section" id="apn-sleep-m1" style="background:#FFFFFF;">
    <div class="apn-s-inner">
      <span class="apn-s-label">YOUR CURRENT STATE</span>
      <h2 class="apn-s-headline">What Your Score Actually Means</h2>
      <div class="apn-s-divider"></div>

      <div id="apn-sleep-score-context">
        <!-- JS will inject score-appropriate context here -->
      </div>

      <p class="apn-s-body">
        The elite benchmark for sleep performance sits at 90 or above. Athletes at that level wake within a 30-minute window every day regardless of the previous night, hit a consistent 65 to 68 degree sleep environment, eliminate blue light exposure by 9pm, and finish their last meal at least 2.5 hours before bed. Their training adaptation is compounding because their recovery architecture is not fighting against their environment. Their slow-wave sleep is long enough that growth hormone pulses fully. Their testosterone synthesis gets the 7.5 to 8 hours of duration it requires. They are not lucky. They are structured.
      </p>

      <div class="apn-s-data-callout">
        <div class="apn-s-data-callout__stat">24%</div>
        <div class="apn-s-data-callout__desc">Average reduction in strength output measured in athletes sleeping 6 hours versus 8 hours over a 2-week period. Not a rounding error. Nearly a quarter of your training yield, gone.</div>
      </div>

      <p class="apn-s-body">
        The performance tax you are paying right now depends on your score, but even a moderate sleep deficit compounds fast. One night of 5 to 6 hours drops reaction time, emotional regulation, and muscular endurance the following day. Two consecutive weeks at that level and testosterone drops 10 to 15%. Your body is doing the math even if you are not.
      </p>

      <!-- Tier-conditional framing -->
      <div class="apn-s-tier-block" data-tier="rookie" style="border-left:4px solid #22C55E; background:#F0FDF4; padding:20px 24px; margin:32px 0;">
        <p style="font-family:'Barlow',sans-serif; font-size:10px; font-weight:700; text-transform:uppercase; letter-spacing:3px; color:#22C55E; margin-bottom:8px;">ROOKIE LEVEL</p>
        <p class="apn-s-body" style="margin:0;">This is the most important single change you will make this month. Every supplement, every training block, every nutrition strategy you layer on top depends on sleep. You cannot out-train a broken sleep system. Close this first.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="apn-s-tier-block" data-tier="competitor" style="border-left:4px solid #F59E0B; background:#FFFBEB; padding:20px 24px; margin:32px 0;">
        <p style="font-family:'Barlow',sans-serif; font-size:10px; font-weight:700; text-transform:uppercase; letter-spacing:3px; color:#F59E0B; margin-bottom:8px;">COMPETITOR LEVEL</p>
        <p class="apn-s-body" style="margin:0;">One gap is holding back all of your other training. Sleep is it. Your nutrition, your hydration, your training volume are doing the right things. But they require an overnight rebuild that is not fully completing. Close this gap and your other gains unlock.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="apn-s-tier-block" data-tier="athlete" style="border-left:4px solid #06A5C5; background:#F0FBFF; padding:20px 24px; margin:32px 0;">
        <p style="font-family:'Barlow',sans-serif; font-size:10px; font-weight:700; text-transform:uppercase; letter-spacing:3px; color:#06A5C5; margin-bottom:8px;">ATHLETE LEVEL</p>
        <p class="apn-s-body" style="margin:0;">You are in the optimization zone. Your basics are solid. Sleep is the last significant drag on your performance ceiling. The gains available to you here are smaller than the rookie jump, but they are the 1% improvements that compound into a visible edge over 90 days.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="apn-s-tier-block" data-tier="elite" style="border-left:4px solid #8B5CF6; background:#F5F3FF; padding:20px 24px; margin:32px 0;">
        <p style="font-family:'Barlow',sans-serif; font-size:10px; font-weight:700; text-transform:uppercase; letter-spacing:3px; color:#8B5CF6; margin-bottom:8px;">ELITE LEVEL</p>
        <p class="apn-s-body" style="margin:0;">At your level, sleep is a precision variable. The margin between good and great lives in your slow-wave sleep duration, your cortisol nadir timing, and whether your HRV is trending up or down week over week. This is not about sleeping more. It is about sleeping better with measurable accuracy.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="apn-s-tier-block" data-tier="champion" style="border-left:4px solid #EF4444; background:#FEF2F2; padding:20px 24px; margin:32px 0;">
        <p style="font-family:'Barlow',sans-serif; font-size:10px; font-weight:700; text-transform:uppercase; letter-spacing:3px; color:#EF4444; margin-bottom:8px;">CHAMPION LEVEL</p>
        <p class="apn-s-body" style="margin:0;">Protect this. You have built a sleep architecture that is working. Any sustained disruption to your sleep system cascades immediately into recovery, testosterone, and mood. Your job this month is maintenance precision, not reinvention.</p>
      </div>

      <!-- Quick Win -->
      <div style="background:#0D0D0D; border-radius:4px; padding:28px 32px; margin:40px 0;">
        <p style="font-family:'Barlow',sans-serif; font-size:10px; font-weight:700; text-transform:uppercase; letter-spacing:4px; color:#06A5C5; margin-bottom:12px;">YOUR QUICK WIN TODAY</p>
        <p style="font-family:'Barlow',sans-serif; font-size:16px; color:#F8FAFB; line-height:1.65; margin-bottom:0;">
          Tonight at 9pm, every screen in your environment goes to night mode or off. Phone, TV, laptop. All of it. This is not about willpower. Blue light in the 400 to 490nm wavelength range directly suppresses melatonin production via intrinsically photosensitive retinal ganglion cells. One night of exposure after 9pm delays your melatonin onset by 60 to 180 minutes, which means your cortisol nadir shifts, your SWS window compresses, and your growth hormone pulse is blunted before you even close your eyes. Do this tonight. Not when you finish reading.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- MODULE 2: WHY THIS IS COSTING YOU -->
  <div class="apn-s-section" id="apn-sleep-m2" style="background:#F4F4F2;">
    <div class="apn-s-inner">
      <span class="apn-s-label">THE SCIENCE</span>
      <h2 class="apn-s-headline">The Mechanism Behind Your Gap</h2>
      <div class="apn-s-divider"></div>

      <p class="apn-s-body">
        Sleep is not passive recovery. It is the most anabolically active 8 hours of your day. During slow-wave sleep (SWS), specifically stages N2 and N3, your pituitary gland releases 70 to 80% of your total daily growth hormone in coordinated pulses. That GH drives muscle protein synthesis, fat mobilization, and tissue repair. The first SWS cycle hits roughly 90 minutes after sleep onset. If your sleep is delayed, fragmented, or cut short, that first GH pulse is the first casualty.
      </p>
      <p class="apn-s-body">
        Cortisol operates on an inverse circadian rhythm to melatonin. For proper sleep onset, cortisol must reach its nadir by 10 to 11pm. In chronically stressed or poorly scheduled athletes, cortisol stays elevated past midnight, competing directly with melatonin for influence over the sleep-wake signal. The result is either delayed onset, fragmented maintenance, or early waking between 2am and 4am, which corresponds precisely to the cortisol rebound period.
      </p>
      <p class="apn-s-body">
        Testosterone synthesis is duration-dependent. The androgen-producing Leydig cells require approximately 7.5 to 8 hours of sleep to complete their full synthesis cycle. Consistent 6-hour nights produce a 10 to 15% reduction in circulating testosterone. Over months, that is not a small number. It is the difference between adequate recovery signal and the blunted training adaptation that athletes chalk up to age, stress, or bad genetics.
      </p>

      <div class="apn-s-data-callout">
        <div class="apn-s-data-callout__stat">-15%</div>
        <div class="apn-s-data-callout__desc">Testosterone reduction measured in healthy young men sleeping 5 hours per night for one week (University of Chicago, 2011). Comparable to 10 to 15 years of aging in terms of hormonal output. One week. Five hours.</div>
      </div>

      <p class="apn-s-body">
        The compounding effect is where most athletes lose. Poor sleep suppresses GH. Suppressed GH impairs muscle repair. Impaired repair means your next training session starts at a deficit, requiring more perceived effort for less actual output. Simultaneously, the adenosine that was not fully cleared during insufficient sleep creates a blunted dopaminergic drive the following day, reducing motivation and focus before you even step into training. Sleep debt does not stay in one lane.
      </p>

      <div class="apn-s-warning">
        <span class="apn-s-warning__label">COMMON MISTAKE</span>
        <p>Compensating for sleep debt with caffeine and pre-workout, then struggling to sleep that night because stimulants are still circulating. Caffeine has a half-life of 5 to 7 hours. A 2pm coffee still has 50mg of active caffeine in your system at 9pm. That delays adenosine reaccumulation, pushing sleep onset back, shortening your SWS window, and restarting the entire deficit cycle the next morning. The pre-workout is not the problem. The timing is.</p>
      </div>

      <!-- Tier-conditional cost block -->
      <h3 style="font-family:Georgia,serif; font-size:22px; color:#0D0D0D; margin:40px 0 16px;">What This Gap Is Costing You Right Now</h3>

      <div class="apn-s-tier-block" data-tier="rookie">
        <p class="apn-s-body">As a Rookie, your sleep gap is costing you the foundational adaptation that makes every training session worth doing. You are training. Your body is signaling for repair. But the repair is incomplete. Every hard session is built on a partially rebuilt structure. The gains that should compound are leaking out overnight.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="apn-s-tier-block" data-tier="competitor">
        <p class="apn-s-body">At Competitor level, your sleep gap is suppressing your hormonal environment. Your nutrition is reasonably locked. Your training is consistent. But your testosterone and GH output are not matching the demand your training is placing on them. You feel like you should be progressing faster. You are right. This is why.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="apn-s-tier-block" data-tier="athlete">
        <p class="apn-s-body">At Athlete level, your sleep gap is a precision drag. Your baseline is solid, but every percentage point of SWS quality you leave on the table is a percentage point of training adaptation you do not capture. Track your HRV alongside sleep quality for two weeks. The correlation will make the cost visible in a way this paragraph cannot.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="apn-s-tier-block" data-tier="elite">
        <p class="apn-s-body">At Elite level, this gap costs you the edge. You are competing against athletes with similar training loads and similar nutrition protocols. The separating variable is recovery quality. Specifically: your deep sleep duration and your cortisol-to-testosterone ratio at 7am. If your morning cortisol is elevated chronically, your anabolic window from the previous night's training is narrowing by the hour.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="apn-s-tier-block" data-tier="champion">
        <p class="apn-s-body">At Champion level, any degradation in your sleep system degrades every other pillar. Your cortisol management is likely tight. Your supplement timing is optimized. But sleep is the non-negotiable multiplier underneath all of it. A three-day sleep disruption will show in your HRV, your mood, and your output before you consciously notice the fatigue. Do not let this slide.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- MODULE 3: THE DIAGNOSIS -->
  <div class="apn-s-section" id="apn-sleep-m3" style="background:#FFFFFF;">
    <div class="apn-s-inner">
      <span class="apn-s-label">SELF-ASSESSMENT</span>
      <h2 class="apn-s-headline">Identify Your Specific Sleep Problem</h2>
      <div class="apn-s-divider"></div>

      <p class="apn-s-body">Your quiz score gives us the what. This assessment identifies the why. Check every symptom that applies to your last 14 days of training and sleep. Be honest. The protocol that follows is calibrated to what you check here.</p>

      <p class="apn-s-body" style="color:#6B7280;">Your current score: <strong id="apn-sleep-score-display" style="color:#06A5C5;"></strong>/100</p>

