  <!-- MODULE 4: THE PROTOCOL -->
  <div class="apn-s-section" id="apn-sleep-m4" style="background:#F4F4F2;">
    <div class="apn-s-inner">
      <span class="apn-s-label">THE PROTOCOL</span>
      <h2 class="apn-s-headline">Your 30-Day Sleep Closure Plan</h2>
      <div class="apn-s-divider"></div>

      <p class="apn-s-body">Four weeks. One gap. Here is exactly what to do. No supplements until Week 3. The environment and timing architecture comes first. Supplements amplify a system that is already built correctly. They do not replace it.</p>

      <!-- WEEK 1 -->
      <div class="apn-s-week">
        <div class="apn-s-week__header">WEEK ONE</div>
        <div class="apn-s-week__title">Build Your Sleep Environment</div>
        <div class="apn-s-week__focus">FOCUS: ENVIRONMENT ARCHITECTURE</div>

        <p class="apn-s-body">One change only this week. The sleep environment. Every modification you make here is permanent infrastructure. Get it right once and it pays dividends every night for years.</p>

        <ul class="apn-s-action-list">
          <li><strong>Temperature: 65 to 68 degrees F.</strong> Your core body temperature must drop 1 to 2 degrees for sleep onset to trigger. A room warmer than 70 degrees actively delays this process. Use a fan, a thermostat, or open a window. Do not skip this. It is the highest-leverage environmental change you can make.</li>
          <li><strong>Blackout your room completely.</strong> Even ambient light from a streetlight or phone LED reduces melatonin secretion via the retinohypothalamic tract. Blackout curtains or a sleep mask. Complete darkness. Test it: you should not be able to see your hand in front of your face.</li>
          <li><strong>Blue light cutoff at 9pm every night.</strong> Set a phone alarm labeled "screens off." After 9pm: phone goes to night mode or face-down, TV off, laptop closed. If you must use a screen, wear blue-light blocking glasses that filter the 400 to 490nm range. This is not negotiable this week.</li>
          <li><strong>Remove your phone from your bedroom entirely.</strong> Use a separate alarm clock. The phone on your nightstand guarantees light exposure, mental activation, and fragmented sleep. Put it in another room by 9:30pm.</li>
        </ul>

        <!-- Tier blocks -->
        <div class="apn-s-tier-block" data-tier="rookie" style="background:#F0FDF4; padding:16px 20px; border-radius:4px; margin:16px 0;">
          <p style="font-family:'Barlow',sans-serif; font-size:10px; font-weight:700; text-transform:uppercase; letter-spacing:3px; color:#22C55E; margin-bottom:8px;">ROOKIE THIS WEEK</p>
          <p class="apn-s-body" style="margin:0;">Pick one of these changes. Just one. The temperature or the blackout. Do it tonight and repeat it every night this week. Add the others next week. Stack one win at a time.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="apn-s-tier-block" data-tier="competitor" style="background:#FFFBEB; padding:16px 20px; border-radius:4px; margin:16px 0;">
          <p style="font-family:'Barlow',sans-serif; font-size:10px; font-weight:700; text-transform:uppercase; letter-spacing:3px; color:#F59E0B; margin-bottom:8px;">COMPETITOR THIS WEEK</p>
          <p class="apn-s-body" style="margin:0;">Implement all four changes this week. The environment is a one-time setup. You are past the one-change-at-a-time stage. Do it all, do it correctly, and move on.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="apn-s-tier-block" data-tier="athlete" style="background:#F0FBFF; padding:16px 20px; border-radius:4px; margin:16px 0;">
          <p style="font-family:'Barlow',sans-serif; font-size:10px; font-weight:700; text-transform:uppercase; letter-spacing:3px; color:#06A5C5; margin-bottom:8px;">ATHLETE THIS WEEK</p>
          <p class="apn-s-body" style="margin:0;">Implement all four. Then baseline your sleep. Use an Oura Ring, Whoop, or Apple Watch sleep data. Record your average sleep score, HRV, and wake time for 7 days before adding anything else. You need a data reference point.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="apn-s-tier-block" data-tier="elite" style="background:#F5F3FF; padding:16px 20px; border-radius:4px; margin:16px 0;">
          <p style="font-family:'Barlow',sans-serif; font-size:10px; font-weight:700; text-transform:uppercase; letter-spacing:3px; color:#8B5CF6; margin-bottom:8px;">ELITE THIS WEEK</p>
          <p class="apn-s-body" style="margin:0;">Environment is likely already good. Audit it with precision. Use a thermometer to verify room temp. Use a lux meter app on your phone to verify darkness. If you wear a tracker, pull your N3 deep sleep average for the last 30 days. That is your baseline. Everything in the next 4 weeks is measured against it.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="apn-s-tier-block" data-tier="champion" style="background:#FEF2F2; padding:16px 20px; border-radius:4px; margin:16px 0;">
          <p style="font-family:'Barlow',sans-serif; font-size:10px; font-weight:700; text-transform:uppercase; letter-spacing:3px; color:#EF4444; margin-bottom:8px;">CHAMPION THIS WEEK</p>
          <p class="apn-s-body" style="margin:0;">Protect what is already working. If your environment is dialed, your task is identifying any recent drift. Shifted wake time. Crept screen time. Warmer room from season change. Audit. Tighten. Hold the standard.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="apn-s-assignment">
          <span class="apn-s-assignment__label">YOUR ASSIGNMENT</span>
          <p>By tonight: set your thermostat or fan to 65 to 68F, install blackout curtains or get a sleep mask, set a 9pm phone alarm labeled "screens off," and move your phone charger to another room. These four changes take 20 minutes to set up and cost you nothing except consistency.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- WEEK 2 -->
      <div class="apn-s-week">
        <div class="apn-s-week__header">WEEK TWO</div>
        <div class="apn-s-week__title">Lock Your Timing Architecture</div>
        <div class="apn-s-week__focus">FOCUS: CIRCADIAN ALIGNMENT</div>

        <p class="apn-s-body">The circadian clock is an actual biological mechanism driven by the suprachiasmatic nucleus (SCN) in the hypothalamus. It runs on 24.2-hour cycles and is anchored by light exposure and wake time. The most powerful lever you have on sleep quality is the most counterintuitive: your wake time, not your bedtime. Consistent wake time calibrates the entire circadian system, which determines when cortisol falls, when melatonin rises, and how deep your SWS goes.</p>

        <ul class="apn-s-action-list">
          <li><strong>Set a fixed wake time and hold it within 30 minutes every single day.</strong> Including weekends. A 2-hour weekend sleep-in is enough to create social jet lag, shifting your cortisol nadir by 60 to 90 minutes and degrading the following week's sleep quality before Monday starts. Pick your time. Hold it.</li>
          <li><strong>No caffeine after 1pm.</strong> Caffeine has a 5 to 7 hour half-life. A 200mg dose at 1pm leaves 100mg active at 7pm and 50mg at 10pm. That 50mg is enough to reduce sleep onset and reduce N3 duration measurably. Move your last caffeine intake to 1pm maximum.</li>
          <li><strong>Finish dinner within 3 hours of your target bedtime.</strong> Late eating elevates core body temperature via thermic effect of food and keeps insulin elevated, both of which delay sleep onset and reduce slow-wave depth. If your bedtime is 10pm, finish eating by 7pm.</li>
          <li><strong>Morning bright light within 30 minutes of waking.</strong> Direct sunlight or a 10,000 lux light therapy lamp for 10 minutes. This signals your SCN to start the cortisol rise and anchors your melatonin timing for that night. The earlier you do this, the earlier melatonin will rise at night.</li>
        </ul>

        <!-- Tier blocks -->
        <div class="apn-s-tier-block" data-tier="rookie" style="background:#F0FDF4; padding:16px 20px; border-radius:4px; margin:16px 0;">
          <p style="font-family:'Barlow',sans-serif; font-size:10px; font-weight:700; text-transform:uppercase; letter-spacing:3px; color:#22C55E; margin-bottom:8px;">ROOKIE THIS WEEK</p>
          <p class="apn-s-body" style="margin:0;">One change: pick a wake time and hold it for 7 days. That is the only assignment this week. No alarm snooze. Same time every day. Do this before anything else in this module.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="apn-s-tier-block" data-tier="competitor" style="background:#FFFBEB; padding:16px 20px; border-radius:4px; margin:16px 0;">
          <p style="font-family:'Barlow',sans-serif; font-size:10px; font-weight:700; text-transform:uppercase; letter-spacing:3px; color:#F59E0B; margin-bottom:8px;">COMPETITOR THIS WEEK</p>
          <p class="apn-s-body" style="margin:0;">Lock wake time and caffeine cutoff. Those are your two non-negotiables this week. Dinner timing is a strong add if your schedule allows it. Morning light is the bonus move.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="apn-s-tier-block" data-tier="athlete" style="background:#F0FBFF; padding:16px 20px; border-radius:4px; margin:16px 0;">
          <p style="font-family:'Barlow',sans-serif; font-size:10px; font-weight:700; text-transform:uppercase; letter-spacing:3px; color:#06A5C5; margin-bottom:8px;">ATHLETE THIS WEEK</p>
          <p class="apn-s-body" style="margin:0;">All four actions this week. Compare your sleep tracker data against last week's baseline. You should already see improvement in sleep latency from the Week 1 environment changes. This week you are targeting deeper SWS by optimizing cortisol timing.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="apn-s-tier-block" data-tier="elite" style="background:#F5F3FF; padding:16px 20px; border-radius:4px; margin:16px 0;">
          <p style="font-family:'Barlow',sans-serif; font-size:10px; font-weight:700; text-spacing:3px; color:#8B5CF6; margin-bottom:8px;">ELITE THIS WEEK</p>
          <p class="apn-s-body" style="margin:0;">Your timing is likely consistent. The precision target this week is cortisol nadir. If you wake consistently between 2am and 4am, your cortisol nadir is too early or too high. Review your dinner timing, alcohol consumption, and late-night stress load. Bloodwork: morning cortisol between 10 and 20 mcg/dL is the range. Elevated morning cortisol that does not drop to nadir by midnight is the signal to address.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="apn-s-tier-block" data-tier="champion" style="background:#FEF2F2; padding:16px 20px; border-radius:4px; margin:16px 0;">
          <p style="font-family:'Barlow',sans-serif; font-size:10px; font-weight:700; text-transform:uppercase; letter-spacing:3px; color:#EF4444; margin-bottom:8px;">CHAMPION THIS WEEK</p>
          <p class="apn-s-body" style="margin:0;">Audit for drift. Has your wake time shifted more than 30 minutes from your ideal? Has caffeine intake crept past 1pm? These small drifts are invisible day to day and devastating over a training block. Tighten them back.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="apn-s-assignment">
          <span class="apn-s-assignment__label">YOUR ASSIGNMENT</span>
          <p>Set your alarm for the same time every morning this week, 7 days in a row. Write the time here mentally and commit: ____. Move your last caffeine to 1pm or earlier starting today. If you train after work and use pre-workout, switch to a non-stimulant stack for evening sessions or train earlier.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- WEEK 3 -->
      <div class="apn-s-week">
        <div class="apn-s-week__header">WEEK THREE</div>
        <div class="apn-s-week__title">Add the Supplement Stack</div>
        <div class="apn-s-week__focus">FOCUS: BIOCHEMICAL SUPPORT</div>

        <p class="apn-s-body">Your environment is built. Your timing is locked. Now supplements do what they are actually designed to do: amplify a system that is already structured correctly. Without Weeks 1 and 2, these products are useful. With them, they are precise.</p>

        <ul class="apn-s-action-list">
          <li><strong>Magnesium Glycinate, 400mg, 60 minutes before bed.</strong> Magnesium modulates GABA-A receptors, the same receptor family targeted by sleep medications but through a gentler, non-dependency pathway. Clinical studies show 400mg magnesium glycinate reduces sleep onset latency by an average of 17 minutes and increases slow-wave sleep duration. Glycinate form is preferred over oxide for bioavailability and to avoid the laxative effect of magnesium oxide.</li>
          <li><strong>Ashwagandha (KSM-66 extract), 600mg, with dinner.</strong> The KSM-66 standardized extract reduces serum cortisol by 27% in double-blind, 8-week trials. Lower evening cortisol is the mechanism. When cortisol reaches its nadir earlier and lower, melatonin onset accelerates and slow-wave sleep depth increases. This is not a sedative. It is a cortisol brake.</li>
          <li><strong>No alcohol this week.</strong> Alcohol is the most disruptive legal substance to sleep quality. It accelerates sleep onset (the sedative effect people mistake for sleep benefit) but increases alpha intrusion into N3 sleep, reduces REM duration by 20 to 25%, and triggers a cortisol rebound in the early morning hours that causes the characteristic 3am wake. If you track sleep, compare an alcohol night to a clean night. The data is unambiguous.</li>
        </ul>

        <!-- Scripture block -->
        <div class="apn-s-scripture">
          <p class="apn-s-scripture__verse">"He grants sleep to those he loves."</p>
          <p class="apn-s-scripture__ref">Psalm 127:2</p>
        </div>

        <p class="apn-s-body">Rest is not weakness. It is not laziness. The belief that sleeping less signals harder work is one of the most costly lies in athletic culture. The discipline of protecting sleep is as serious as the discipline of showing up to train. Your body rebuilds in the night. Let it.</p>

        <!-- Tier blocks -->
        <div class="apn-s-tier-block" data-tier="rookie" style="background:#F0FDF4; padding:16px 20px; border-radius:4px; margin:16px 0;">
          <p style="font-family:'Barlow',sans-serif; font-size:10px; font-weight:700; text-transform:uppercase; letter-spacing:3px; color:#22C55E; margin-bottom:8px;">ROOKIE THIS WEEK</p>
          <p class="apn-s-body" style="margin:0;">Start with magnesium glycinate only. 400mg, 60 minutes before bed. One product. Evaluate for 7 days before adding ashwagandha. Do not add both at once when you are just building your system.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="apn-s-tier-block" data-tier="competitor" style="background:#FFFBEB; padding:16px 20px; border-radius:4px; margin:16px 0;">
          <p style="font-family:'Barlow',sans-serif; font-size:10px; font-weight:700; text-transform:uppercase; letter-spacing:3px; color:#F59E0B; margin-bottom:8px;">COMPETITOR THIS WEEK</p>
          <p class="apn-s-body" style="margin:0;">Both products this week. Magnesium at 9:30pm, ashwagandha with dinner. Eliminate alcohol completely for this week. Observe whether your 2am wakes reduce. That is the direct marker of cortisol improvement from the ashwagandha.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="apn-s-tier-block" data-tier="athlete" style="background:#F0FBFF; padding:16px 20px; border-radius:4px; margin:16px 0;">
          <p style="font-family:'Barlow',sans-serif; font-size:10px; font-weight:700; text-transform:uppercase; letter-spacing:3px; color:#06A5C5; margin-bottom:8px;">ATHLETE THIS WEEK</p>
          <p class="apn-s-body" style="margin:0;">Full stack. Add Foundation (D3+K2) with your largest meal of the day. Vitamin D deficiency is associated with reduced N3 sleep duration. If your bloodwork shows D levels below 40 ng/mL, 2000 to 5000IU daily is appropriate. Compare your sleep tracker N3 duration this week against your Week 1 baseline.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="apn-s-tier-block" data-tier="elite" style="background:#F5F3FF; padding:16px 20px; border-radius:4px; margin:16px 0;">
          <p style="font-family:'Barlow',sans-serif; font-size:10px; font-weight:700; text-transform:uppercase; letter-spacing:3px; color:#8B5CF6; margin-bottom:8px;">ELITE THIS WEEK</p>
          <p class="apn-s-body" style="margin:0;">Full precision stack. Magnesium glycinate 400mg at 9:30pm. Ashwagandha KSM-66 600mg with dinner. Foundation D3+K2 with largest meal. Track your sleep score, N3 duration, HRV, and morning resting HR daily. You need data, not guesses. Pull a 7-day average at the end of the week.</p>
        </div>
