        <div class="apn-s-week__title">Measure, Review, and Lock</div>
        <div class="apn-s-week__focus">FOCUS: HRV BASELINE AND OUTCOME MEASUREMENT</div>

        <p class="apn-s-body">The gap is closing. Week 4 is about measuring how much it has closed and building the permanent system that sustains it. If you have not yet started tracking HRV, this week is when that starts.</p>

        <ul class="apn-s-action-list">
          <li><strong>Establish your HRV baseline.</strong> Take a morning HRV reading at the same time every day this week, immediately upon waking, before getting out of bed. Use Whoop, Oura, Garmin, or a free app like HRV4Training. Record 7 consecutive readings. This number is your parasympathetic recovery indicator. As your sleep quality improves, HRV trends up. It is the most objective data point you have on whether this protocol is working.</li>
          <li><strong>Compare sleep quality to Week 1.</strong> Pull your average sleep score or subjective rating from Week 1 versus this week. If you do not track, use a simple 1 to 10 subjective score each morning. Measure: how long to fall asleep, whether you wake mid-night, how rested you feel at your fixed wake time.</li>
          <li><strong>Lock the non-negotiables into permanent infrastructure.</strong> The three items that stay forever: fixed wake time within 30 minutes, blue light cutoff at 9pm, and magnesium glycinate before bed. Everything else is adjustable. These three are not. Write them down and put them somewhere visible.</li>
          <li><strong>Identify what still needs work.</strong> If onset is still slow, revisit temperature and stress management. If maintenance waking persists, examine late-evening eating and alcohol. If quality feels low despite the protocol, look at sleep duration and consider whether you are cutting your window short by circumstance.</li>
